Temperance also is not desirable for its own sake, but because it bestows peace of mind, and soothes the heart with a tranquillizing sense of harmony. For it is temperanee that warns us to be guided by reason in what we desire and avoid. Nor is it enough to judge what it is right to do or to leave undone3 we also need to abide by our judgment. Most nien however lack tenacity of purpose; their resolution weakens and suecumbs as soon as the fair form of pleasure meets their gaze, and they surrender them- selves prisoners to their passions, failing to foresce the inevitable result. Thus for the sake of a pleasure at once small in amount and unnecessary, and one which they might have procured by other means or even denied themselves altogether without pain, they incur serious disease, or loss of fortune, or disgrace, and not infrequently become liable to the penalties of the law and of the courts of justice.
